A Weekly Profile of Guyanese Excellence
At Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Dr. Sharmila Persaud is performing some of the world&rsquo;s most complex brain surgeries. But every morning, she looks at a photo on her desk: her grandmother&rsquo;s wooden house in Berbice, where she grew up without electricity.
The Journey &ldquo;People ask me how I got from there to here,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud says, gesturing around her state-of-the-art operating suite. &ldquo;I tell them: I got here because I started there.&rdquo;
Born in New Amsterdam in 1985, Sharmila was the first in her family to attend university. Her father drove a taxi. Her mother sold vegetables at the market. They had one dream: their daughter would become a doctor.
Against the Odds The path wasn&rsquo;t easy:
Studied by kerosene lamp when power was out (which was often) Walked 3 miles to school in Berbice rain Helped her mother at the market before classes Won a scholarship to Queen&rsquo;s College in Georgetown Graduated top of her class at University of Guyana medical school A scholarship to Johns Hopkins came next. Then residency. Then fellowship. Now, at 40, she&rsquo;s one of the leading neurosurgeons in North America.
The Guyana Connection But success hasn&rsquo;t severed her roots√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùit&rsquo;s strengthened them.
Dr. Persaud:
Returns to Guyana quarterly for medical missions Has trained 15 Guyanese doctors in neurosurgery techniques Established a scholarship fund for Berbice students Donated equipment to Georgetown Public Hospital Mentors young Guyanese doctors remotely &ldquo;I&rsquo;m successful because Guyana made me who I am,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;The work ethic, the resilience, the determination√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthat&rsquo;s all Guyana.&rdquo;
The Berbice Spirit She tells the story of performing a 14-hour surgery on a young patient last year. Exhausted, she almost asked her team to take over.
&ldquo;Then I remembered my mother standing in the market for 16 hours a day, never complaining. I thought: if she could do that selling vegetables, I can do this saving a life.&rdquo;
The surgery succeeded.
Advice for Young Guyanese Dr. Persaud is often asked to speak at schools in Guyana. Her message is consistent:
&ldquo;Your circumstances don&rsquo;t define your destination. I studied by lamplight. You have electricity and internet. You have no excuse√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùand unlimited potential.&rdquo;
She pauses. &ldquo;But also: never forget where you came from. Success means nothing if you don&rsquo;t bring others along.&rdquo;
The Return Plan Dr. Persaud has a five-year plan: establish Guyana&rsquo;s first dedicated neurosurgery center in Georgetown.
&ldquo;We train excellent doctors in Guyana,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But then we lose them because we don&rsquo;t have the facilities to use their skills. That has to change.&rdquo;
She&rsquo;s already raised $2 million toward the project. The Guyanese diaspora is contributing. So are international partners impressed by Guyana&rsquo;s potential.
&ldquo;My grandmother&rsquo;s generation left Guyana for opportunity,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud reflects. &ldquo;My generation left Guyana for education. The next generation? They should stay in Guyana for both.&rdquo;
Beyond Medicine Outside the hospital, Dr. Persaud maintains her Guyanese identity fiercely:
Cooks pepperpot for colleagues every Christmas Teaches her children Creolese phrases Wears her Guyana flag pin on her white coat Serves on the board of the Baltimore Guyanese Association &ldquo;I&rsquo;m Guyanese first,&rdquo; she says simply. &ldquo;Everything else is just what I do, not who I am.&rdquo;
The Photo That photo on her desk√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthe one of her grandmother&rsquo;s house in Berbice?
&ldquo;It reminds me every day why I do this work,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;And reminds me that no matter how far I&rsquo;ve come, that&rsquo;s still home.&rdquo;
Dr. Sharmila Persaud proves what&rsquo;s possible when Guyanese excellence meets opportunity. And more importantly, she&rsquo;s ensuring the next generation won&rsquo;t have to leave Guyana to reach it.
Patriots&rsquo; Portfolio is a weekly feature celebrating successful Guyanese at home and abroad√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùtheir journeys, their achievements, and their continued connection to the land that shaped them.

A Monthly Feature Celebrating Guyana&rsquo;s Progress
Walk down Main Street today, and you&rsquo;ll see something remarkable happening. Georgetown, once known for its colonial charm mixed with urban challenges, is undergoing a transformation that would have seemed impossible just five years ago.
The Numbers Tell the Story Since 2020, Georgetown has seen:
40+ new businesses opening on Main Street alone $500 million invested in waterfront development 300% increase in tourism infrastructure 12 new hotels under construction or recently opened Beyond the Statistics But the real story isn&rsquo;t in the numbers‚Äîit&rsquo;s in the people.
Rajiv Persaud, who returned from Toronto last year to open a tech startup, puts it simply: &ldquo;I left because I didn&rsquo;t see opportunity. I came back because now I see nothing but opportunity.&rdquo;
His company, GuyanaTech Solutions, now employs 45 Guyanese developers, many of whom were considering emigration before finding high-paying tech jobs at home.
The Waterfront Renaissance The Demerara River waterfront, once avoided after dark, now bustles with evening activity. New restaurants serve everything from traditional pepperpot to international fusion cuisine. Families stroll along newly lit promenades. Street vendors sell coconut water and plantain chips to office workers on lunch breaks.
&ldquo;My grandmother remembers when this was the heart of Georgetown,&rdquo; says Michelle Chen, owner of River&rsquo;s Edge Caf√©. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not building something new‚Äîwe&rsquo;re reclaiming something we lost.&rdquo;
Challenges Remain Not everything is perfect. Traffic congestion has worsened with prosperity. Housing prices are rising faster than wages for some. The infrastructure upgrades can&rsquo;t keep pace with demand.
But these are, as Mayor Patricia Williams notes, &ldquo;the problems of a city that&rsquo;s growing, not dying.&rdquo;
The Diaspora Returns Perhaps most telling: the flow is reversing. More Guyanese are returning home than leaving. The &ldquo;brain drain&rdquo; that plagued the nation for decades is becoming a &ldquo;brain gain.&rdquo;
At the University of Guyana, Professor David Singh sees it in his classrooms: &ldquo;Students used to ask me how to get into foreign universities. Now they ask me how to build businesses here.&rdquo;
Looking Forward The transformation of Georgetown is just beginning. Plans are underway for:
A modern public transportation system Expansion of the Cheddi Jagan International Airport A new convention center to attract regional conferences Smart city initiatives including free public WiFi Green spaces and urban parks What It Means Georgetown&rsquo;s transformation is more than physical infrastructure. It represents a psychological shift‚Äîfrom a nation that exported its talent to one that nurtures and retains it.
Walking through Bourda Market on a Saturday morning, you hear it in conversations. Pride. Hope. Excitement about tomorrow.
One vendor, selling mangoes and plantains, summed it up: &ldquo;My children don&rsquo;t have to leave anymore. That&rsquo;s everything.&rdquo;
The Guyanese Horizon This monthly feature will chronicle Guyana&rsquo;s journey‚Äîthe successes, the challenges, the people building tomorrow. Because understanding where we&rsquo;re going requires seeing where we are.
Georgetown is rising. And so is Guyana.
The Guyanese Horizon is a monthly feature celebrating progress, honoring heritage, and documenting the transformation of our nation.

Government Goes High-Tech! üì± Ministry of Public Works proud to unveil their revolutionary new app: &ldquo;Report-A-Hole&rdquo;
Minister at launch ceremony: &ldquo;This app will TRANSFORM infrastructure management in Guyana!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh, sitting front row, already downloading it before Minister finish talking.
Speedeet whisper: &ldquo;Bai, you even know how to use app?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;How hard it could be? Is just button and camera!&rdquo;
Famous last words.
Monday Morning: De Beginning 6:00 AM - Uncle Ramesh Mission Starts
Uncle Ramesh wake up early, fully charge he phone, and decide to become Guyana&rsquo;s #1 pothole reporter.
&ldquo;If government want data, I go GIVE dem data!&rdquo;
He start driving from Buxton to Georgetown, eyes peeled.
6:15 AM - First Pothole
BOOM! Giant crater near Buxton market.
Uncle Ramesh pull over, open app:
Snap photo ‚úì Add location ‚úì Severity rating: 8/10 Description: &ldquo;Big hole, 2 feet wide, 6 inches deep&rdquo; SUBMIT ‚úì App say: &ldquo;Thank you! Report #00001 received. Response time: 3-5 business days.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh feel like Superman. &ldquo;I saving de nation, one pothole at a time!&rdquo;
8:30 AM - The Marathon Session
By time Uncle Ramesh reach Georgetown, he done report 47 potholes.
Each one with photo. Each one with GPS. Each one with detailed notes.
He phone battery: 23% He data plan: Crying He satisfaction level: Through de roof!
Speedeet call: &ldquo;Bai, where you dey? We was supposed to meet 7:30!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Sorry! I was busy doing CIVIC DUTY!&rdquo;
Tuesday: De Waiting Game Uncle Ramesh check app every hour.
All 47 reports showing: &ldquo;UNDER REVIEW üîç&rdquo;
&ldquo;Good,&rdquo; he think. &ldquo;Government working hard!&rdquo;
He notice other people reporting too. App now showing 1,247 reports nationwide.
Uncle Ramesh to himself: &ldquo;Guyanese finally participating in democracy! Beautiful!&rdquo;
He report 23 MORE potholes just for good measure.
Wednesday: De Plot Thickens Uncle Ramesh now at 70 total reports.
Status still: &ldquo;UNDER REVIEW üîç&rdquo;
But he notice something funny - that massive pothole near LBI? It got 15 DIFFERENT reports from 15 different people!
Same hole, 15 angles, 15 descriptions.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Everybody want credit for reporting de same hole! This is competitive civic duty!&rdquo; üòÇ
Thursday: DISASTER STRIKES! 6:00 AM
Uncle Ramesh open app.
Screen show: &ldquo;ERROR 503: Server Unavailable&rdquo;
He try again. Same thing.
He try 5 more times. STILL error.
Uncle Ramesh starting to panic. &ldquo;But&hellip; but&hellip; I had 3 new potholes to report!&rdquo;
2:00 PM - Government Statement
Ministry release message:
&ldquo;Report-A-Hole app experiencing technical difficulties due to OVERWHELMING response. We never anticipated THIS MANY potholes would be reported. Server capacity being upgraded. Back online soon.&rdquo;
Wilar: &ldquo;Dey never anticipated how many potholes Guyana have? Where dey been driving?&rdquo;
Speedeet: &ldquo;Probably helicopter.&rdquo; üòÇ
Friday: DE BIG REVEAL Morning - App Back Online!
Uncle Ramesh immediately check he 70 reports.
Status changed!
He eyes get BIG.
EVERY. SINGLE. REPORT. now showing: &ldquo;COMPLETED ‚úÖ&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh JUMP out he chair!
&ldquo;SEVENTY POTHOLES FIX IN ONE WEEK?! This is MIRACLE! This is RECORD! This is&hellip; this is&hellip; I gotta go see this!&rdquo;
He grab he keys, RUSH to he car, and start de Grand Inspection Tour.
De Grand Inspection Tour (AKA: De Disappointment) Pothole #1 (Buxton Market):
Uncle Ramesh park. Get out. Look at de road.
Pothole STILL DEY.
But now&hellip; it got a bright YELLOW CIRCLE paint around it.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Wha&hellip; what is THIS?!&rdquo;
Pothole #7 (Better Hope):
Still there. Yellow circle.
Pothole #15 (Enmore):
Still there. Yellow circle.
Uncle Ramesh starting to see a pattern.
Pothole #23 (Lusignan):
WAIT! This one ACTUALLY FILL! Real asphalt! Smooth road!
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Okay, okay, we getting somewhere!&rdquo;
Potholes #24-46:
All still there. All with pretty yellow circles.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;I living in a coloring book?!&rdquo;
Pothole #47 (Kitty Market):
Also ACTUALLY filled!
FINAL COUNT:
Potholes fixed: 2 Potholes painted: 68 Uncle Ramesh&rsquo;s faith in technology: Shaken Uncle Ramesh Calls Ministry He HAVE to understand this.
Ring ring
&ldquo;Ministry of Public Works, how can I help you?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes, I report 70 potholes, app say &lsquo;COMPLETED,&rsquo; but only 2 fix. De other 68 just have PAINT on dem!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Please hold, sir.&rdquo;
Hold music for 15 minutes - ironically, is Bob Marley &ldquo;Everything&rsquo;s Gonna Be Alright&rdquo;
Technical Support guy (Jason) come on:
&ldquo;Hello! You must be User #00001! Sir, you&rsquo;re FAMOUS here! Minister mentioned you in morning briefing!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;That nice and all, but what about DE POTHOLES?!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;Ah yes, let me explain. The yellow circles mean we VERIFIED the location. The pothole is now in our system for SCHEDULING.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;So &lsquo;COMPLETED&rsquo; means y&rsquo;all COMPLETE de PAPERWORK?!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;Well&hellip; the report PROCESSING is completed, yes. The actual REPAIR is a separate phase based on priority, budget, and resources.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;So when de ACTUAL holes getting fix?&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;That depends on various factors, sir. But your reports are VERY helpful for our planning database!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Planning database?! I could PLANT CASSAVA in some of these holes!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;I understand your frustration, sir. Would you like to speak with a supervisor?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Never mind. Thank you.&rdquo; Click
De App Store Reviews (Comedy Gold) By Friday evening, de review section is FIRE:
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Speedeet: &ldquo;Best comedy app of 2026! I laugh every time I open it! Forget Netflix!&rdquo;
‚≠ê Wilar: &ldquo;One star because I can&rsquo;t give ZERO. My car suspension file a formal complaint.&rdquo;
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Anonymous: &ldquo;The yellow circles are aesthetic! Georgetown now look like abstract art installation! Very modern!&rdquo;
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê SarahG: &ldquo;App work perfect. Government response need software update.&rdquo;
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê RameshB: &ldquo;10/10 entertainment value. Also my route now has glow-in-the-dark navigation! Potholes still there but at least I can SEE dem at night!&rdquo; üòÇ
‚≠ê‚≠ê TaxiDriver: &ldquo;I now tell tourists: &lsquo;Welcome to Guyana! See those yellow circles? That&rsquo;s where government THINKING about progress!&rsquo;&rdquo;
‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê KrishnanC: &ldquo;The circles are PERFECT diameter. Clearly someone took measurements. That&rsquo;s dedication to mediocrity!&rdquo;
Ministry Respond to Reviews &ldquo;We appreciate all feedback. Yellow marking is STANDARD INTERNATIONAL PRACTICE for infrastructure maintenance. We have processed 3,847 reports with 89% initial assessment completed. Repairs ongoing in phases based on available resources.&rdquo;
Wilar: &ldquo;Phases? We going need PHASES for de phases!&rdquo;
Week 2: DE BIG UPDATE! Government announce &ldquo;Report-A-Hole 2.0&rdquo; with &ldquo;exciting new features&rdquo;:
Feature #1: &ldquo;Virtual Pothole Filling&rdquo; Use your phone camera to see how the road WOULD look if pothole was filled!
Uncle Ramesh try it: &ldquo;So I can SEE a smooth road on my phone while my CAR bouncing through de real hole?! BRILLIANT!&rdquo; üòÇ
Feature #2: &ldquo;Leaderboard&rdquo;
See who reports most potholes!
Current standings:
#1: RameshB (127 reports) üèÜ #2: SpeedyDriver (89 reports) #3: TaxiGuyGT (76 reports) Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;I winning at something nobody should have to compete in!&rdquo;
Feature #3: &ldquo;Social Sharing&rdquo; Share your pothole reports with #MyPotholeStory!
Speedeet: &ldquo;Is this for SYMPATHY or COMEDY?&rdquo;
Feature #4: &ldquo;AI Pothole Prediction&rdquo; Algorithm predicts where NEXT potholes will form!
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Dey can PREDICT future potholes but can&rsquo;t FIX current ones?! We living in science fiction!&rdquo; üòÇ
Wilar: &ldquo;Maybe de AI can fill de holes too. Just send robot.&rdquo;
Three Weeks Later: De Twist Uncle Ramesh checking app again.
Something changed:
Original 70 potholes: 15 ACTUALLY FIXED! ‚úÖ 8 more scheduled for next week 47 still rocking their yellow circles Uncle Ramesh grudgingly admit: &ldquo;Okay&hellip; 15 is better than 0. I suppose.&rdquo;
Speedeet: &ldquo;You still using de app?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;EVERY DAY! Just report 3 more this morning! And that pothole near de market from Week 1? Dey ACTUALLY fix it today!&rdquo;
Wilar: &ldquo;So&hellip; it working?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;EVENTUALLY! Rome wasn&rsquo;t build in a day. Georgetown roads won&rsquo;t fix in a week. But at least now we have NUMBERED yellow circles! Is progress!&rdquo; üòÇ
De Final Irony Uncle Ramesh now explain de app to EVERYBODY:
&ldquo;See, you report de pothole. Dey paint yellow circle. You wait. Maybe it get fix. Maybe not. But at least you PARTICIPATED in democracy! And your route now look like Connect-De-Dots game!&rdquo;
Government actually send Uncle Ramesh certificate: &ldquo;Most Active Citizen Reporter - January 2026&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh frame it and hang it in he living room.
Right next to he &ldquo;I Survived De Pothole Apocalypse&rdquo; bumper sticker.
MORAL OF DE STORY: Technology can&rsquo;t fix everything. But it CAN make you laugh while you dodging potholes! üòÇüá¨üáæ
